AN ACT making an appropriation for allocation to nonprofit organizations to
provide programs for the creation and maintenance of school gardens;
and providing other matters properly relating thereto.
THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF NEVADA, REPRESENTED IN
SENATE AND ASSEMBLY, DO ENACT AS FOLLOWS:
1 Section 1. 1. There is hereby appropriated from the State General Fund to
2 the Other State Education Programs Account in the State General Fund for the cost
3 of creating and maintaining programs for school gardens that meet the requirements
4 of subsection 3 the following sums:
5 For the Fiscal Year 2025-2026 .................................. [$2,000,000] $200,000
6 For the Fiscal Year 2026-2027 .................................. [$2,000,000] $200,000
7 2. The Department of Education shall allocate the money appropriated by
8 subsection 1 to nonprofit organizations to provide at a public school a program for a
9 school garden which meets the requirements set forth in subsection 3.
10 3. For a nonprofit organization to receive an allocation of money to provide a
11 program for a school garden pursuant to subsection 2, the program must:
12 (a) Create and maintain a school garden at the school.
13 (b) Have a curriculum that:
14 (1) Includes a comprehensive science, technology, engineering and
15 mathematics school garden program. Such a program must include, without
16 limitation, a science, technology, engineering and mathematics curriculum for
17 outdoor or hydroponic gardens for pupils in kindergarten through grade 12 that is
18 tailored to pupils of the appropriate grade levels at the school;
19 (2) Is written specifically for Nevada and the desert environment of
20 Nevada;
21 (3) Complies with the standards of content and performance for a course of
22 study in science adopted by the State Board of Education pursuant to NRS 389.520;

Senate Amendment No. 870 to Senate Bill No. 104 Page 4
1 (4) Uses experiential learning or project-based learning to teach science,
2 technology, engineering, arts and mathematics;
3 (5) Is designed with the assistance of teachers and other educational
4 personnel with experience at the appropriate grade levels at the school; and
5 (6) Involves supervised learning experiences for the pupils at the school in
6 a classroom and a school garden.
7 (c) Provide the school with assistance from members of the community,
8 including, without limitation, trained educators, local farmers and local chefs.
9 (d) Provide pupils with the:
10 (1) Ability to operate a farmer’s market to sell the produce from the school
11 garden; and
12 (2) Opportunity to have a local chef or employee of a school who works in
13 food services demonstrate how to cook a meal using the produce grown from the
14 school garden.
15 (e) Establish garden teams comprised of teachers and, if such persons are
16 available, parents and members of the community. Each garden team shall meet at
17 least once each month.
18 (f) Require any local nonprofit or community-based organization which will
19 provide services to implement the program for a school garden to have at least 2
20 years of experience implementing such a program.
21 4. Money allocated pursuant to subsection 2 may be used to:
22 (a) Provide professional development for teachers regarding the:
23 (1) Use of a school garden to teach pupils with disabilities, including,
24 without limitation, training for teaching such pupils science, technology,
25 engineering and mathematics curriculum and vocational training to create a career
26 path in horticulture;
27 (2) Development and implementation of science, technology, engineering,
28 arts and mathematics curricula that incorporate the use of a school garden;
29 (3) Development and implementation of training that may be provided to a
30 group or individually to teachers in how to establish and maintain school gardens to
31 increase the time teachers allocate to teaching science, technology, engineering and
32 mathematics; and
33 (4) Development and implementation of a food safety plan designed to
34 ensure that food grown in a school garden is properly handled and safe to sell and
35 consume;
36 (b) Pay for any travel expenses associated with the attendance of a teacher at
37 any training or conference relating to school gardens; and
38 (c) Pay for the costs of a conference regarding school gardens held in this
39 State.
40 5. As used in this section:
41 (a) “Public school” has the meaning ascribed to it in NRS 385.007.
42 (b) “School garden” includes, without limitation, a hydroponic garden.
43 Sec. 2. Upon acceptance of the money allocated pursuant to section 1 of this
44 act, a nonprofit organization agrees to:
45 1. Prepare and transmit a report to the Interim Finance Committee on or
46 before October 1, 2026, that describes each expenditure made from the money
47 allocated pursuant to section 1 of this act from the date on which the money was
48 received by the nonprofit organization through June 30, 2026;
49 2. Prepare and transmit a final report to the Interim Finance Committee on or
50 before October 1, 2027, that describes each expenditure made from the money
51 allocated pursuant to section 1 of this act from the date on which the money was
52 received by the nonprofit organization through June 30, 2027; and

